{{nihongo|'''''Cleopatra no Mahō'''''|クレオパトラの魔宝|Kureopatora no Mahō|lit. "Cursed Treasure of Cleopatra"}} is a Japanese [[role-playing video game]] developed and published by [[Square (video game company)|Square]] for the [[Family Computer Disk System]], and released in Japan on 24 July 1987.<ref name="famitsu"/> The game's music was composed by [[Nobuo Uematsu]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archive.na.square-enix.com/uematsu/profile/index.html |title=N's Profile |publisher=[[Square Enix]] |access-date=2016-02-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150325000200/http://archive.na.square-enix.com/uematsu/profile/index.html |archive-date=2015-03-25 |url-status=live}}</ref>

== Gameplay ==
Players explore an [[Egypt]]ian town and ruins from a [[first person (video games)|first-person perspective]]. The game combines role-playing game elements with an [[adventure game]]-like interface. Players may purchase items from shops, though some shopkeepers must be defeated in battle before trading. Battles are [[turns, rounds and time-keeping systems in games|turn-based]], with options to fight, use items, or flee. Players accumulate [[experience point]]s by succeeding in battle and "level up" after gaining enough experience, which increases their [[health (gaming)|stamina]]. [[Random encounter|Randomly encountered battles]] with enemies may happen at any time, including when paused to examine the inventory.<ref name="itmedia">{{cite web |url=http://gamez.itmedia.co.jp/games/articles/0606/13/news048.html |title=アドベンチャー＋RPG≒ゲームブック「クレオパトラの魔宝」 |trans-title=Cursed Treasure of Cleopatra: RPG + Adventure = Story-driven game |author=ゲイムマン |date=13 June 2006 |language=Japanese |website=ITmedia Gamez |publisher=ITmedia |accessdate=20 May 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150601150754/http://gamez.itmedia.co.jp/games/articles/0606/13/news048.html |archive-date=1 June 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>

== Plot ==
The [[player character]], Daisuke Kusano, is the son of an archaeologist who disappeared while searching for the Tears of Isis, artifacts once owned by [[Cleopatra]]. During the man's excavation for the Tears, demons appeared and abducted him. The boy soon learns that he must find the Tears in order to save his father.<ref name="itmedia"/><ref name="square">{{cite web |url=http://www.jp.square-enix.com/archive/kureopatora/ |script-title=ja:クレオパトラの魔宝 |trans-title=Cursed Treasure of Cleopatra |website=Square Enix Japan |publisher=[[Square Enix]] |language=Japanese |accessdate=20 May 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150420081403/http://www.jp.square-enix.com/archive/kureopatora/ |archive-date=20 April 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> Over the course of the adventure, Daisuke visits the [[Great Sphinx of Giza]], the [[Temple of Kom Ombo]], a tower of sand, and an underground [[labyrinth]]. At the end of the game, he discovers that the demons had been disguised as the kindly shopkeeper. Daisuke receives the last Tear of Isis upon defeating the demons, which summons the ghost of Cleopatra, who releases Daisuke's father from imprisonment.<ref name="itmedia"/>

==Development==
[[Nobuo Uematsu]] composed the music for the game.<ref name=timing>{{cite web|url= https://news.denfaminicogamer.jp/nicolive/uematsu/4|accessdate=June 8, 2020|title=『キングスナイト』の曲は『ドルアーガの塔』を意識した──作曲家・植松伸夫が語るスクウェア初期作品の思い出|publisher=Den Faminico Gamer|date=December 14, 2016}}</ref> When developing the game for both the Famicom and the Famicom Disk System (FDS), there were technical differences such as a smaller amount of memory on the FDS which led to a more difficult process creating the same graphics.<ref name=answer1>{{cite book|page=191|date=February 2018|title=The Untold History of Japanese Game Developers|volume=3|author=Szczepaniak, John|publisher=SMG Szczepaniak}}</ref>

